# Build to headset (fastest dev loop)

When the user says "build to headset" / "build to quest" / "build it" (dev intent), do the
**fastest incremental Build-And-Run** to the connected Quest. Do not ask which config; default to this.

## Procedure
1. Confirm the Quest is connected (only if a prior build failed to install):
   `& "D:\UnityEditor\6000.4.2f1\Editor\Data\PlaybackEngines\AndroidPlayer\SDK\platform-tools\adb.exe" devices`
   (Quest 3 id `2G0YC5ZH1S0348`. Shell is PowerShell: call exes with `&`, separate cmds with `;`.)
2. Only if `.cs` scripts changed this session, force a recompile first (else skip — recompiling is slow):
   `refresh_unity` (force) and wait for `editor_state.isCompiling == false`. Skipping when scripts
   changed causes "script class layout incompatible editor vs player".
3. Trigger the build (async) via Unity MCP and poll `status` with the returned `job_id`:
   `manage_build { action:"build", target:"android", output_path:"Builds/Android/FantasyVR.apk",
   options:["auto_run","compress_lz4"] }`
   - `auto_run` installs + launches on the headset automatically.
4. Confirm success by the returned status and/or the APK timestamp at `Builds/Android/FantasyVR.apk`.

## Keep it fast — do NOT
- **Never pass `clean_build`** unless a build is genuinely broken (it wipes the IL2CPP/gradle cache → minutes slower).
- **Never toggle the `development` flag or `scripting_backend`** between builds — switching busts the cache and forces a full rebuild. Pick one config (this one) and always reuse it.
- **Don't change `output_path`** — same path reuses incremental artifacts.
- Don't rebake lighting or switch platforms as part of a build.

## Notes
- The MCP link drops during the build/domain reload; wait and reconnect, then poll `status`.
- Build scene order lives in Build Settings (boot scene = index 0, currently `Assets/Scenes/Dungeon.unity`).
